elements.2211.03177_9d28f9c0ebf938b70ff479bb16cf1: End-to-end deep neural networks (DNNs) have become state-of-the-art (SOTA) for solving inverse problems
elements.2211.03177_55c7ab3ab67f133fe2cf52564d78a: Despite their outstanding performance, during deployment, such networks are sensitive to minor variations in the training pipeline and often fail to reconstruct small but important details, a feature critical in medical imaging, astronomy, or defence
elements.2211.03177_0c68fb900076e3bd1a4543f2ef1c0: Such instabilities in DNNs can be explained by the fact that they ignore the forward measurement model during deployment, and thus fail to enforce consistency between their output and the input measurements
elements.2211.03177_7d597cc165bdc45b5d335d0f01719: To overcome this, we propose a framework that transforms any DNN for inverse problems into a measurement-consistent one
elements.2211.03177_a291b99c71e7cd61892d6759c657b: This is done by appending to it an implicit layer (or deep equilibrium network) designed to solve a model-based optimization problem
elements.2211.03177_bc486d4a9a014cece26bee4230787: The implicit layer consists of a shallow learnable network that can be integrated into the end-to-end training
elements.2211.03177_441e3719047dfff605639bee49131: Experiments on single-image super-resolution show that the proposed framework leads to significant improvements in reconstruction quality and robustness over the SOTA DNNs.
elements.2211.03177_277348a43f37e91b67c9e2032fcf9: Image super-resolution, ADMM, implicit layers, deep equilibrium networks, fixed-point iterations.
elements.2211.03177_27ae8ae04b40b8cef8b687e59b113: We consider the problem of reconstructing a vector
elements.2211.03177_9a0420af71feaf2ed2825b7122659: of which we have only a few linear, noisy measurements
elements.2211.03177_0ad1c1c73fc7d559ea34b91b5e8c7: Such a linear inverse problem is challenging since, even when there is no noise, the system
elements.2211.03177_b6d701cc249a243b68cccc142f26a: contains infinitely many solutions, among which the one we seek,
elements.2211.03177_e5e65e4ab1151a561ca54d34933f6: by solving an optimization problem that balances (or constrains) measurement fidelity and a regularizer encoding prior knowledge about
elements.2211.03177_e832eaedbf4333becb698f2f97b77: A long-standing challenge is to devise regularizers that, while computational tractable, effectively describe classes of signals.
elements.2211.03177_d51d87e0ce29caf586b7bc43ac37c: State-of-the-art (SOTA) methods for image reconstruction tasks such as super-resolution, MRI reconstruction, or inpainting, leverage the power of deep neural networks (DNNs) to directly learn a map from the measurements to the corresponding reconstructed signal
elements.2211.03177_c6d58b3cfd2de7bbecc826138cf83: Despite their extraordinary performance, such end-to-end schemes are unreliable, failing, for example, to detect small, unusual signals absent in the training data
elements.2211.03177_5bd58c493b03c21a7db4e26808b2d: Part of the reason is that during deployment they ignore the forward measurement model, that is,
elements.2211.03177_98067cf7fd925fd4567b4b73e785a: , even when the model is known
elements.2211.03177_caf261684eb8345d83e99bcec12a2: Moreover, end-to-end DNNs for image reconstruction require retraining whenever the measurement operator
elements.2211.03177_fb6924bb9369b0708e41ddd312b3a: Both shortcomings are absent in classical optimization-based methods, albeit at the cost of poorer performance
elements.2211.03177_51a965f3fa069ab07423d2caf98de: Recent work has thus tried to blend classical and DNN approaches to get the benefits of both
elements.2211.03177_cc1dc04de6ae55d534de5844759e6: We categorize such methodologies as deep unrolling networks (DUNets), plug-and-play methods (PnP), post-processing (PP), and deep equilibrium models (DEQs), and briefly review them in

elements.2211.03177_3209455a998b05b20bfb427d38058: We propose a framework, MCNet, for transforming any DNN for inverse problems into a measurement-consistent one.
elements.2211.03177_f6df04e213c6ed2c2245d63f8a1c6: We design an efficient training algorithm based on DEQ techniques
elements.2211.03177_7dc56c376df2ba175d9534f0113e6: By interpreting an ADMM algorithm to solve the problem in the implicit layer as a fixed-point iteration, we leverage the implicit function theorem to train the network without ever unrolling the iterations

elements.2211.03177_aadf502ad152b8cea9f67a1e714ec: We establish conditions under which the fixed-point algorithm converges in the forward and backward passes.
elements.2211.03177_9dd8068745a08b067fe547869b17d: Extensive results on single-image super-resolution show that, with respect to prior methods, MCNet not only makes the DNN outputs measurement-consistent, but also yields significant gains in quality, despite having significantly fewer learnable parameters.
elements.2211.03177_ea4b765044d8f1558416a09c88a50: We briefly overview work that integrates DNNs into classical optimization-based approaches.

elements.2211.03177_734a502547afc746360e3d6bd354c: We proposed a framework to transform any existing DNN for solving inverse problems into a measurement-consistent network, when the acquisition model is known precisely

elements.2211.03177_8e55e1193c0bcd219d2cd1537ef9d: Although the proposed method requires solving an optimization problem during training and inference, the additional computational cost is justified in applications that require precise fidelity to measurements, for example, in areas in medicine, astronomy or defence

elements.2211.03177_8b9a6591ee4f0cee645ab5a68b73f: End-to-end deep neural networks (DNNs) have become the state-of-the-art (SOTA) for solving inverse problems
